metadata.name: Winter Jacket #28
metadata.description:
Inspired by vintage textile patterns. Once minted your patterns maintain their design while stretching to accommodate changes in canvas size.

There are no rarity attributes assigned to this artwork, its value is intended to be determined by viewer aesthetic alone.

This artwork was created using p5js and utilizes the p5.pattern library created by Taichi Sayama.

metadata.name: Planets #95
metadata.description:
A complete step aside from my normal work. I've been feeling nostalgic for old games and old science fiction recently. I wanted to bring those ideas together and create a feeling of comfort with this piece.

This generative token produces a random planet from a variety of types. Some are inspired by real planets, others by planets from fiction. Each planet can have moons or other nearby planets in the background. If the planet has its axis tilted it will have a summer and winter side, visible in its biomes. Very hot planets may have oceans only near the poles if at all, very cold planets may be frozen everywhere but the equator. 

Press down on the keyboard to see a map view in equirectangular projection.

And most of all enjoy your very own planet!

metadata.name: Cardinal Directions #42
Rondelle, Listen #28
metadata.description:
Tap to start sound. Tap to mute.

Inspired by the glass rondelles which hung from the windowsill in my childhood home. I ask myself what would these rondelles sound like if they reflected sound instead of light? To me, I hear hopeful harmonies of memories past, but they are falling in and out of tune and they are occluded by the muffled noise of time.

When a rondelle is minted, a transaction hash is injected into its code. All colors, patterns, sounds, and motions are generated deterministically from this transaction hash.

As the rondelle loads in your browser, a real-time generative algorithm writes tones, noise, feedback, and distortion to three looping audio buffers. During playback, oscillations in pan, pitch, and volume track the visual oscillations among the rondelle's color rings.

Rarity features are included. The least common rondelles are closed center, monochrome, smol, split color, and square.

Made with Web Audio and p5js. Minted on fxhash beta. Idlebit, 2021.

metadata.name: Disegnatori #237
metadata.description:
Each disegnatore learns a different portion of a city map, looking at it stroke by stroke and creating a probabilistic Markov model of the sequences of relative angles and distances, tracing the outline of each building in that portion of the map. This way, each disegnatore has a different internal understanding of the city.

It then starts from the middle of the canvas and wanders out, stroke by stroke, probability by probability, trying not to intersect any previously drawn outlines and avoiding the edges of the canvas until a predetermined number of edges have been drawn.

The Markov chain drawing model is created during execution from a text file representation of a city map.

Open live to see your disegnatore drawing or to resize.

metadata.name: radium #5
metadata.description:
Simulating the idea  about if the human eye could get able to see the radiation frequencies.

"radium" is trying to bring the wondering of if its would be possible naturarely, how it would be if we see ultraviolet lights, radio waves and things like that, as some other earth creatures...

The variations is on some patterns that goes through looking like an the edge of a black hole, planet rings, and in some times even a landscape...

The soul of "radium" is the colormaps that are set to randomize the time its inserting new colors, the form of paint, intensity, the diffusion of grainy noise and the pattern of growth to simulate the frequencies emanation.
 A  sequential pulse growing or a rectroative pulse that grows  after it goes and came back in the opposite direction.




this is a work in p5.js

Omar Lobato Neto, 28/08/2022
Pompéu, Minas Gerais.
